.. This changelog follows the format at https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.0.0/ ; this project adheres to Semantic Versioning.
    Added      for new features.
    Changed    for changes in existing functionality.
    Deprecated for soon-to-be removed features.
    Removed    for now removed features.
    Fixed      for any bug fixes.
    Security   in case of vulnerabilities.
    Docs       for any documentation changes



[0.13.0] - 2026-05-19
---------------------

**Fixed**:
    - ``README.md`` (or whichever file is declared as ``readme`` in
      ``pyproject.toml``) is now copied into ``build/compiled/`` alongside
      ``pyproject.toml`` before the wheel is built, so PyPI receives the
      package description instead of showing *"The author of this package has
      not provided a project description"*.

**Docs**:
    - ``windows_exe.rst`` ‚Äî *How the wheel is built* section updated to
      document that the readme file is copied into ``build/compiled/``.


[0.12.0] - 2026-05-19
---------------------

**Added**:
    - ``scaldys-project ci markdown`` ‚Äî check-only Markdown formatting check
      that mirrors the *Prettier format* step in the GitHub Actions CI
      pipeline.  Prettier runs in ``--check`` mode so no files are modified.
      Included as the final step of ``ci all``.

      The check-only pre-commit configuration is bundled inside the
      ``scaldys-project`` wheel
      (``scaldys_project/resources/.pre-commit-check-config.yaml``) and
      resolved via ``importlib.resources`` at runtime.  Consumer projects do
      **not** need a ``.pre-commit-check-config.yaml`` file in their root.

    - ``scaldys-project format`` ‚Äî new command group for auto-formatting files
      in place:

      - ``format python`` ‚Äî rewrites Python source files with
        ``uv run ruff format .``
      - ``format markdown`` ‚Äî rewrites Markdown files with
        ``uv run pre-commit run prettier --all-files``
      - ``format all`` ‚Äî runs ``format python`` then ``format markdown``

    - ``scaldys_project/resources/.pre-commit-check-config.yaml`` ‚Äî check-only
      pre-commit configuration (Prettier with ``--check``) bundled as a package
      resource inside the wheel.  Used exclusively by ``ci markdown``; consumer
      projects are not required to provide this file.

**Changed**:
    - Configuration file renamed from ``scaldys.toml`` to ``scaldys-project.toml``.

      The file name now unambiguously identifies which tool owns it within the
      ``scaldys`` project umbrella.  Using just ``scaldys.toml`` was ambiguous
      when a consuming project also uses other tools under the same umbrella
      (e.g. ``scaldys-template``); naming the file after the specific tool
      (``scaldys-project``) removes that ambiguity entirely and is consistent
      with the hyphenated package name convention.  No settings, sections, or
      defaults are changed.

      .. note::
         **Breaking change for consuming projects.**  Any project that provides
         a ``scaldys.toml`` file must rename it to ``scaldys-project.toml``.
         The file contents remain identical; only the filename changes.

      - Documentation file ``scaldys_toml_reference.rst`` renamed to
        ``scaldys_project_toml_reference.rst`` and its
        ``.. _scaldys_toml_reference:`` label updated to
        ``.. _scaldys_project_toml_reference:`` accordingly.
      - All internal source code, tests, and documentation updated to reference
        ``scaldys-project.toml`` and ``scaldys_project_toml_reference``.

**Removed**:
    - ``sphinx-apidoc`` integration removed from the documentation build pipeline.

      ``internal_doc_dirs`` (the ``[docs]`` key that triggered a
      ``sphinx-apidoc`` pre-pass before ``sphinx-build``) has been removed
      from ``DocsConfig`` and from ``scaldys-project.toml``.
      ``sphinx_apidoc_exe_path`` has been removed from
      ``BaseBuildEnvironment``.

      The ``[docs]`` section now has a single key: ``public_doc_dirs``.
      All documentation units are built by ``sphinx-build`` directly;
      API reference pages should be hand-authored using ``.. automodule::``
      directives rather than generated by ``sphinx-apidoc``.

      .. note::
         **Breaking change for consuming projects.**  Remove any
         ``internal_doc_dirs`` key from your ``scaldys-project.toml``.
         The key is silently ignored by ``load_config()`` (unknown TOML keys
         are not an error), but it no longer has any effect.

**Fixed**:
    - Pure-Python wheel now correctly tagged ``py3-none-any`` when no
      ``compiled_modules`` are declared.

      ``Compiler._build_wheel()`` previously wrote a ``setup.py`` that forced
      a platform-specific wheel tag unconditionally.  The intent was to prevent
      setuptools from downgrading a wheel that contains pre-built ``.pyd``
      extensions to ``py3-none-any``, but the same ``setup.py`` was injected
      even when ``compiled_modules = []`` (the default), causing a pure-Python
      build to produce a spurious platform tag such as ``cp313-cp313-win_amd64``.
      The ``BinaryDistribution`` ``setup.py`` is now only written when
      ``compiled_modules`` is non-empty; otherwise any stale ``setup.py`` from a
      previous build is removed, allowing setuptools to apply the correct
      ``py3-none-any`` tag.

**Docs**:
    - ``docs/manual/source/developers/markdown_formatting.rst`` expanded with a
      full technical explanation: how the pre-commit config is split between the
      project-level ``.pre-commit-config.yaml`` and the check-only config
      bundled in the wheel, the ``ci`` (check-only) vs ``format``
      (fix-in-place) contract, and a scenario-by-scenario comparison of local
      git hook, ``ci markdown``, ``format markdown``, and GitHub Actions
      behaviour.
    - ``docs/manual/source/developers/contributing.rst`` updated to list all
      ``ci`` and ``format`` subcommands with their intent; cross-reference text
      updated to reflect the project-file / bundled-resource split.
    - ``docs/manual/source/users/cli_usage.rst`` updated with the ``format``
      command group (tree, ``format all``, ``format python``, ``format
      markdown`` sections) and the corrected ``ci markdown`` description
      (bundled config, no project file required).


[0.11.0] - 2026-05-17
---------------------

**Added**:
    - ``ci`` subcommand group: runs quality checks locally, mirroring the
      GitHub Actions pipeline step-for-step.  All ``ci`` commands operate on
      the **current working directory** (not the project root), so they work
      for any project::

          scaldys-project ci all          # run every step; stops on first failure
          scaldys-project ci lint         # uv run ruff check .
          scaldys-project ci format       # uv run ruff format --diff .
          scaldys-project ci typecheck    # uv sync && uv run pyright ./src

    - ``test`` command: runs the project test suite via pytest::

          scaldys-project test            # uv run pytest -v --durations=0 --cov --cov-report=xml

    - ``publish`` command: uploads the binary wheel from ``dist/`` to PyPI
      via ``uv publish``.  Refuses to publish pure-Python wheels (platform
      tag ``none-any``) to prevent Cython source code from being exposed on
      PyPI.  Also refuses when multiple binary wheels are found in ``dist/``
      (stale build artifacts)::

          scaldys-project publish         # upload binary wheel to PyPI
          scaldys-project publish --test  # upload to TestPyPI instead

      This command is intended for consuming projects that use Cython-compiled
      extensions and therefore cannot rely on automated CI publishing (which
      would produce a pure-Python source distribution).  ``scaldys-project``
      itself continues to publish automatically via GitHub Actions.

**Changed**:
    - CLI refactored from a single monolithic ``__main__.py`` into a
      structured ``cli/`` package, following the same layout as
      ``scaldys-template``.  The new layout:

      .. code-block:: text

          cli/
          ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cli.py              # Typer app, logging, command wiring
          ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ utils.py            # shared console, find_project_root()
          ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ commands/
              ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cmd_build.py    # build subcommands (unchanged behaviour)
              ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cmd_check.py    # check command (unchanged behaviour)
              ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cmd_ci.py       # new ci subcommands
              ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ cmd_publish.py  # new publish command
              ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ cmd_test.py     # new test command

      ``__main__.py`` is now a minimal entry point that imports ``app`` from
      ``cli/cli.py``.  The ``pyproject.toml`` entry point is unchanged
      (``scaldys_project.__main__:app``).

      A single ``Console`` instance is now shared across logging and all
      build commands (via ``cli/utils.py``) to prevent Rich live-display
      conflicts.

**Removed**:
    - ``ci build`` subcommand (``uv build``).  The command was redundant with
      ``scaldys-project build all`` and actively misleading for binary-wheel
      projects: running ``uv build`` locally produces a pure-Python wheel,
      which is the wrong artifact for projects that use Cython compilation.
      The ``ci`` group now covers only quality gates (lint, format, typecheck),
      matching the scope of the GitHub Actions ``ci.yml`` workflow.

**Docs**:
    - *Publishing* guide in the developer manual updated with a *Why automated
      publishing?* section that explains the design rationale: ``scaldys-project``
      is pure-Python and open-source, so CI-built wheels are the correct and
      complete artifact and OIDC Trusted Publishing is the most secure release
      mechanism.  The section also contrasts with consuming projects that use
      Cython-compiled extensions and must publish manually via
      ``scaldys-project publish``.


[0.10.0] - 2026-05-17
---------------------

**Docs**:
    - Added *Publishing* guide to the developer manual covering PyPI Trusted
      Publishing setup, GitHub environment configuration, workflow files,
      version bump procedure, release triggering, and TestPyPI dry run.


[0.9.0] - 2026-05-17
---------------------

**Changed**:
    - Configuration file renamed from ``builder.toml`` to ``scaldys.toml``.

      The file name now matches the project name (``scaldys-project``) rather
      than describing the tool's original role.  No settings, sections, or
      defaults are changed.

      .. note::
         **Breaking change for consuming projects.**  Any project that provides
         a ``builder.toml`` file must rename it to ``scaldys.toml``.  The file
         contents remain identical; only the filename changes.

      - Documentation file ``builder_toml_reference.rst`` renamed to
        ``scaldys_toml_reference.rst`` and its ``.. _builder_toml_reference:``
        label updated to ``.. _scaldys_toml_reference:`` accordingly.
      - All internal source code, tests, and documentation updated to reference
        ``scaldys.toml`` and ``scaldys_toml_reference``.


[0.8.0] - 2026-05-17
---------------------

**Changed**:
    - Project renamed from ``scaldys-builder`` to ``scaldys-project``.

      - PyPI package name changed: ``scaldys-builder`` ‚Üí ``scaldys-project``.
      - Python package (import name) changed: ``scaldys_builder`` ‚Üí ``scaldys_project``.
      - CLI entry point changed: ``scaldys-builder`` ‚Üí ``scaldys-project``.
      - Source directory renamed: ``src/scaldys_builder/`` ‚Üí ``src/scaldys_project/``.

      All internal imports, documentation references, configuration files, and
      lock file entries are updated accordingly.  No functional changes are
      introduced in this release.

      .. note::
         **Breaking change.**  Any project depending on ``scaldys-builder`` must
         update its dependency declaration (e.g. in ``pyproject.toml``) to
         ``scaldys-project``.  Any code that imports from ``scaldys_builder``
         must be updated to import from ``scaldys_project``.


[0.7.0] - 2026-05-17
---------------------

**Changed**:
    - Build output split into two top-level directories with distinct purposes:

      - ``dist/`` ‚Äî PyPI-conventional directory for the distributable wheel.
        The ``dist/wheels/`` subdirectory is eliminated; the wheel is now
        written directly into ``dist/``, matching the convention expected by
        ``twine upload dist/*`` and ``uv publish``.

      - ``artifacts/`` ‚Äî new top-level directory for all other build outputs
        that are not published to PyPI.  Replaces the previous use of ``dist/``
        for non-wheel artefacts.

      Previous ``dist/`` paths and their ``artifacts/`` replacements:

      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+
      | Old path                         | New path                                |
      +==================================+=========================================+
      | ``dist/wheels/<name>.whl``       | ``dist/<name>.whl``                     |
      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+
      | ``dist/portable/``               | ``artifacts/portable/``                 |
      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+
      | ``dist/installer/``              | ``artifacts/installer/``                |
      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+
      | ``dist/documentation/``          | ``artifacts/documentation/``            |
      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+
      | ``dist/pyruntime/``              | ``artifacts/pyruntime/``                |
      +----------------------------------+-----------------------------------------+

      .. note::
         **Breaking change for consuming projects.**  Any Inno Setup ``.iss``
         script that references ``dist\portable\``, ``dist\installer\``, or
         ``dist\documentation\`` must be updated to reference
         ``artifacts\portable\``, ``artifacts\installer\``, and
         ``artifacts\documentation\`` respectively.

    - ``build clean`` now removes ``artifacts/`` in addition to ``build/`` and
      ``dist/``.  The OneDrive slow-sync warning is updated to mention all three
      directories.

    - ``builder.toml`` deployment-mode documentation updated to reflect the new
      directory layout.

**Added**:
    - Pre-build compliance check for package installation in ``pyinstaller`` mode.
      ``check_compliance()`` now verifies that the project package is installed
      in the active virtual environment (i.e. a dist-info entry is present and
      discoverable by ``importlib.metadata``).

      A missing dist-info previously caused ``copy_metadata()`` in the
      PyInstaller hook to raise a ``StopIteration`` deep inside PyInstaller,
      producing a cryptic traceback with no indication of the fix.  The check
      now catches this condition before the build starts and reports:

      .. code-block:: text

         ‚úó Package 'my-app' is not installed in the active virtual environment
           (no dist-info found). Run 'uv sync' (or 'pip install -e .') and retry.

      This most commonly occurs after renaming the project (changing ``name``
      in ``pyproject.toml``) without reinstalling.


[0.6.1] - 2026-05-15
---------------------

**Fixed**:
    - ``build all`` in ``wheel_only`` mode now distributes built documentation
      to ``dist/documentation/`` as documented in ``builder.toml``.
      Previously, the entire packaging step was skipped in this mode, so
      Sphinx built the docs to ``build/<name>/html/`` but they were never
      copied to ``dist/``.

      A new ``Packager._distribute_docs()`` method handles this: it copies
      each ``public_doc_dirs`` entry from ``build/<name>/html/`` to
      ``dist/documentation/<name>/``.  A *Distributing documentation* step
      now appears in the ``build all`` progress bar for ``wheel_only`` mode
      (previously absent).


[0.6.0] - 2026-05-14
---------------------

**Changed**:
    - Output subdirectory ``dist/pyinstaller/`` renamed to ``dist/portable/``
      to describe the content (copy-and-run standalone bundle) rather than the
      tool that produced it.

    - Output subdirectory ``dist/setup/`` renamed to ``dist/installer/``
      to describe the artifact type (Windows installer) rather than the
      conventional filename of the executable it contains.

    - ``builder.py`` renamed to ``__main__.py``, making ``scaldys-project``
      consistent with the project layout it enforces on consuming projects.
      The module is now also runnable as ``python -m scaldys_project``.
      The ``pyproject.toml`` entry point updated accordingly
      (``scaldys_project.__main__:app``).

    - Developer manual updated to reflect the rename in the module layout
      diagram and execution-flow description (``architecture.rst``) and in
      the new-platform-builder guide (``extension_points.rst``).

    - ``[docs]`` configuration keys renamed to better express their purpose:
      ``dist_dirs`` ‚Üí ``public_doc_dirs`` (documentation units destined for
      end users, bundled into the installer) and ``apidoc_dirs`` ‚Üí
      ``internal_doc_dirs`` (documentation units for project developers, not
      distributed to end users).  Updated in ``config.py``, ``docs.py``,
      ``windows/builder.py``, all tests, ``builder.toml``, and the full
      user manual.

**Docs**:
    - User manual synchronised with the codebase changes introduced in 0.4.0‚Äì0.6.0.
      All affected pages updated in one pass


[0.5.0] - 2026-05-10
---------------------

**Added**:
    - ``_build_wheel()`` build step: after PyInstaller completes, a ``.pyd``-only
      distribution wheel is built from ``build/compiled/`` (which contains compiled
      ``.pyd`` extensions only, no Python source).  The step patches a copy of the
      project's ``pyproject.toml`` to restrict setuptools package discovery to the
      project package (excluding ``extra_hooks/``) and to declare ``*.pyd`` files as
      package data.  The resulting wheel is placed in ``dist/`` ready for
      ``uv pip install --find-links``.

    - Online and offline installer modes: the build supports an optional
      ``PythonRuntimeDir`` variable in the Inno Setup ``.iss`` script.  When set,
      the pre-built PythonRuntime directory is embedded inside ``setup.exe``
      (offline mode); when absent, Python is downloaded at install time via ``uv``
      (online mode).

    - ``.python-version`` compliance requirement: ``scaldys-project`` now rejects
      a build if the target project's root does not contain a ``.python-version``
      file.  This file serves as the single source of truth for the Python version
      shared between the build pipeline, the wheel build, and the PythonRuntime
      setup script.

**Changed**:
    - Compliance rule set extended with the ``.python-version`` check (see
      ``scaldys-project check`` and the *Project Compliance* guide).


[0.4.0] - 2026-05-08
---------------------

**Added**:
    - Generic documentation system: every immediate subdirectory of ``docs/``
      is now treated as an independent documentation unit.  There is no longer
      a fixed set of names ‚Äî subdirectory names are freely choosable.  All
      units are discovered and built automatically; no configuration is needed
      to add a new unit.

    - Engine auto-detection: the documentation engine for each unit is
      determined by inspecting its contents.  A ``source/conf.py`` file
      selects Sphinx; a ``mkdocs.yml`` selects MkDocs (detected but not yet
      built ‚Äî a warning is logged and the unit is skipped).  Units whose
      directory matches neither marker also produce a warning and are skipped.

    - ``[docs]`` section in ``builder.toml``:

      - ``dist_dirs`` ‚Äî list of subdirectory names whose built HTML is copied
        into the distribution artefacts (``dist/portable/documentation/<name>/``).
        Defaults to ``[]`` (no documentation distributed).

      - ``apidoc_dirs`` ‚Äî list of subdirectory names that require a
        ``sphinx-apidoc`` pre-pass before ``sphinx-build``.  Defaults to
        ``[]``.  This replaces the previously hardcoded behaviour of always
        running ``sphinx-apidoc`` for a directory named ``developer_guide``.

    - ``DocEngine`` enum and ``_detect_engine()`` function in
      ``scaldys_project.common.docs``, providing a testable, reusable engine
      detection primitive.

    - ``WindowsBuilder._any_sphinx_docs()`` helper: replaces the hardcoded
      check for ``docs/manual/`` when determining whether Sphinx must be
      present at pre-flight time.

**Changed**:
    - Distribution path for documentation changed from the single fixed
      destination ``dist/portable/documentation/help files/`` to
      ``dist/portable/documentation/<name>/`` (one sub-folder per entry in
      ``[docs] dist_dirs``).

      .. note::
         **Breaking change for consuming projects.**  Any Inno Setup ``.iss``
         script that references the old ``documentation\help files\`` path
         must be updated to reference ``documentation\<name>\`` instead.

    - ``DocumentationBuilder`` refactored: the two hardcoded methods
      ``build_user_guide()`` and ``build_developer_guide()`` are replaced by
      a generic ``build()`` / ``_build_one()`` / ``_build_sphinx()`` loop
      that works for any number of doc units.

    - ``BaseBuildEnvironment`` no longer exposes the four hardcoded path
      attributes ``user_guide_dir_path``, ``user_guide_build_dir_path``,
      ``developer_guide_dir_path``, and ``developer_guide_build_dir_path``.
      Paths are now derived at call-time from the directory name.

    - Documentation updated throughout: *Documentation Building* guide
      rewritten for the generic system; *Configuration* guide updated with
      the new ``[docs]`` section; *Project Layout*, *CLI Reference*,
      *Overview*, *Quick Start*, and *Windows Installer* pages updated to
      reflect the new paths and behaviour.



[0.4.0] - 2026-05-14
---------------------

**Added**:
    - Three Windows deployment modes, controlled by ``deployment_mode`` in
      ``builder.toml`` (``[windows]`` section):

      - ``"pyinstaller"`` (default) ‚Äî existing behaviour: PyInstaller bundles
        the application into a self-contained executable directory; Inno Setup
        produces a ``setup.exe``.

      - ``"pyruntime"`` ‚Äî PyInstaller is not used.  A managed Python virtual
        environment (``PythonRuntime``) is deployed alongside the application
        via Inno Setup.  Intended for applications that must coexist with
        Quarto, Jupyter, or another tool that requires a real Python
        interpreter.  ``setup_pyruntime.ps1``, ``uv.exe``, and
        ``.python-version`` are staged into ``dist/portable/bin/`` so the
        installer can set up the runtime at install time.

      - ``"wheel_only"`` ‚Äî builds a binary distribution wheel only; no
        installer is created.  The Inno Setup script and launcher files are
        not required.  Use for packages distributed via ``pip`` or ``uv``.

    - ``dist/wheels/`` ‚Äî unified top-level output directory for the binary
      distribution wheel in all three modes.  In ``pyruntime`` mode the wheel
      is additionally staged to ``dist/portable/wheels/`` so Inno Setup can
      bundle it into the installer.

    - ``WindowsBuilder.build_distribution()`` ‚Äî new method that runs the
      Windows distribution pipeline without the documentation step.  Used by
      the new ``build windows`` CLI command.

    - ``WindowsBuilder._distribution_steps()`` ‚Äî internal helper that returns
      the mode-dependent step list, shared by ``main()`` and
      ``build_distribution()``.

    - ``WindowsBuilder._run_steps()`` ‚Äî internal helper that drives the Rich
      progress bar for a given step list; avoids duplicating the
      progress-bar loop between ``main()`` and ``build_distribution()``.

**Changed**:
    - CLI redesigned ‚Äî the ``build windows`` sub-group and its five commands
      (``exe``, ``installer``, ``all``, ``docs``, ``clean``) are replaced by
      four flat commands directly under ``build``:

      - ``build all`` ‚Äî documentation + full Windows distribution pipeline
        (replaces ``build windows all``)
      - ``build docs`` ‚Äî Sphinx documentation only
        (replaces ``build windows docs``)
      - ``build windows`` ‚Äî Windows distribution only, no docs rebuild
        (replaces the separate ``build windows exe`` + ``build windows installer``
        pair; behaviour is mode-dependent)
      - ``build clean`` ‚Äî delete ``build/`` and ``dist/``
        (replaces ``build windows clean``)

    - Compliance checking is now mode-dependent.  Rules 5‚Äì8 (packaging
      directory, ``.iss`` script, launcher scripts) are only enforced when
      ``deployment_mode`` is not ``"wheel_only"``.  Rule 9
      (``.python-version``) is only enforced in ``"pyruntime"`` mode.

    - ``Compiler.build()`` ‚Äî PyInstaller is only invoked when
      ``deployment_mode == "pyinstaller"``.

    - ``Compiler._build_wheel()`` ‚Äî wheel output path changed from
      ``dist/portable/bin/wheels/`` to ``dist/wheels/`` (all modes).

    - ``Packager.prepare_windows_files()`` ‚Äî ``setup_pyruntime.ps1``,
      ``.python-version``, and ``uv.exe`` are staged only in ``pyruntime``
      mode; wheel staging to ``dist/portable/wheels/`` is likewise restricted
      to ``pyruntime`` mode.

    - ``Packager.run_innosetup()`` ‚Äî passes ``/DPyruntimeMode=1`` and
      optionally ``/DPythonRuntimeDir`` only in ``pyruntime`` mode.

    - ``Packager.build()`` ‚Äî returns early with an informational log message
      in ``wheel_only`` mode (no installer step).

    - ``WindowsBuildEnvironment`` ‚Äî new ``dist_wheels_dir_path`` attribute
      (``dist/wheels/``).

    - Pre-flight checks and compliance checks are skipped for irrelevant tools
      depending on the active mode (e.g. PyInstaller not checked in
      ``pyruntime`` or ``wheel_only`` mode; Inno Setup not checked in
      ``wheel_only`` mode).

    - User manual updated throughout: new *Windows Distribution Modes* guide
      (replaces *PyInstaller Executable Bundling*), updated *Windows Installer
      Creation*, *CLI Reference*, *Configuration*, *Project Compliance*,
      *Project Layout*, *Overview*, *Quick Start*, and
      ``builder.toml ‚Äî Full Reference`` pages.

    - ``builder.toml`` reference updated with the new ``deployment_mode`` key
      and revised ``bundle_pyruntime`` documentation (now explicitly scoped to
      ``pyruntime`` mode).

**Docs**:
    - ``architecture.rst`` updated: execution flow section revised for the
      new CLI structure and mode-aware step list; ``BuildConfig`` dataclass
      diagram extended with ``DocsConfig``, ``deployment_mode``, and
      ``bundle_pyruntime``.


[0.3.0] - 2026-05-07
---------------------

**Added**:
    - Project compliance checking: ``scaldys-project`` now validates the target
      project's required files and structure before running any build step.  All
      issues are reported together in a single pass so they can be fixed at once.
      If any requirement is not met the tool exits cleanly with a descriptive
      message rather than failing mid-build with a cryptic error.

      Compliance is checked automatically at the start of ``build windows exe``,
      ``build windows installer``, and ``build windows all``.

    - New top-level command ``scaldys-project check``: runs the full compliance
      check on the current project without triggering a build.  Useful for
      verifying a freshly cloned project or diagnosing issues.

    - New documentation page *Project Compliance* (In-Depth Guides section):
      lists all eight compliance rules with descriptions, the commands each rule
      applies to, and cross-reference links to the relevant guide sections.

**Fixed**:
    - Project names containing hyphens (e.g. ``my-app``) are now normalised to
      underscores when resolving Python package paths (e.g. ``src/my_app/``,
      ``my_app/__main__.py``, ``--collect-submodules my_app``), matching the
      Python import system convention (PEP 503 / PEP 508).  The raw project name
      is preserved for artefact naming (executable, ``.iss`` script, launcher
      scripts, icon).


[0.2.0] - 2026-05-04
---------------------

**Added**:
    - Sphinx-based user manual under ``docs/manual/``, structured in three sections:

      *Users*

        - Overview ‚Äî what ``scaldys-project`` does, the build pipeline diagram,
          and two clear entry paths (new project vs. existing project)
        - Installation ‚Äî adding ``scaldys-project`` as a dev dependency with
          extras, external tool requirements, and installation verification
        - Quick Start ‚Äî step-by-step project setup and first build walkthrough
        - CLI Reference ‚Äî complete reference for every command and option
        - In-Depth Guides: project layout and build output, ``builder.toml``
          configuration, documentation building, Cython compilation, Windows
          EXE bundling, and Inno Setup installer creation

      *Developers*

        - Architecture ‚Äî module layout, three-class composition pattern,
          execution flow, configuration loading, and an explanation of why
          ``compile_runner.py`` runs as a subprocess
        - Extension Points ‚Äî design conventions and how to add Cython modules,
          build steps, or a new platform builder
        - Contributing ‚Äî dev environment setup, testing, linting, publishing,
          and testing changes against a consuming project

      *About*

        - Changelog, authors, license, and get-help page

    - ``docs/manual/Makefile`` and ``make.bat`` for building the HTML manual
    - ``licenses/`` directory with license copies and credit information for
      all third-party tools used by ``scaldys-project``
    - ``licenses/README.md`` index listing each tool's license type, upstream
      URL, and link to the corresponding local license file


